  "prompt": "Why does Ben Affleck\u2019s Batman Kill people intentionally?",
  "response": "Ben Affleck's portrayal of Batman in the DC Extended Universe (DCEU) is notably darker and more aggressive than previous iterations of the character. This version of Batman, seen most prominently in films like \"Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice\" and \"Justice League,\" diverges from the traditional depiction of Batman who typically adheres to a strict no-kill rule.\n\nThere are several reasons behind this intentional shift in character:\n\n1. **Character Evolution and Context**: In \"Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice,\" Batman is depicted as a more seasoned and cynical hero who has suffered significant emotional and physical trauma over the years. The loss of Robin (implied through the vandalized suit in the Batcave) and the increasing brutality he faces in Gotham have pushed him towards a darker path. This is a Batman who is disillusioned and believes that more extreme measures are necessary to combat the escalating threats.\n\n2. **Storytelling and Thematic Choices**: Director Zack Snyder aimed to present a more realistic and morally ambiguous world. His interpretation of Batman fits within this vision, where the lines between hero and vigilante are blurred. Snyder's storytelling often deals with themes of gods among men and the consequences of power and vengeance, so Batman's willingness to kill reflects these broader themes.\n\n3. **Batman\u2019s Conflict with Superman**: At the beginning of \"Batman v Superman,\" Batman sees Superman as an existential threat to humanity. His aggressive stance\u2014including potentially lethal tactics\u2014reflects his desperation and fear. This paranoia leads him to make decisions that he might not otherwise make, further driving him to act in ways that are more uncharacteristically ruthless.\n\n4. **Narrative Impact**: The decision to have Batman kill was also meant to highlight his eventual redemption arc. By showing Batman at such a low and broken state, it leaves room for his character to evolve and potentially return to his more heroic roots in future films. This arc culminates somewhat in \"Justice League,\" where Batman begins to work alongside other heroes and adopts a more hopeful outlook.\n\nUltimately, Ben Affleck's Batman killing people intentionally was a creative decision meant to add depth to the character and fit the darker, more serious tone of the DCEU films during Snyder's tenure. This interpretation has sparked debate among fans and critics, contributing to the ongoing discourse about the character's fundamental nature and principles.",
